Assignment 3

Peace Without a Piece

    Guns are powerful tools.  They allow even the weakest man to defend his family and honor.  They provide a permanent solution to many problems in life.  John Singleton introduces this idea early on in his film, Boyz ‘N the Hood, through young Doughboy’s dialogue with his friends after his brother’s football is stolen by some teenagers.  Doughboy expresses deep hatred for these hoodlums and wishes he could kill them.  However, he learns the hard way that he is not physically strong enough to commit such an act, demonstrated by his inability to reclaim his brother’s property, implying that he wishes he had a means for killing them.  The easiest means for this would be the potent gun.  While Tre Styles tries to offer up a peaceful solution, offering his football to Ricky, Doughboy disintegrates this resolution by revealing the football was a gift from Ricky’s father – probably the only gift Ricky, raised by his single mother, ever received from him.  Enduring this situation suddenly seems much more unfair to the audience of this film.   The image of Doughboy heroically firing a “piece” in an effort to reclaim his brother’s property and teach some older kids a lesson starts to creep into the filmgoer’s imagination.  Before the audience can entertain this thought further, a sympathetic member of the hoodlum pack spirals the ball toward Ricky.  Guns provide a seemingly permanent solution to many problems in life.  However, most of those problems are only temporary ones.  Anti-violent messages such as this are ingrained in every aspect of the film, showing that violence is never a proper means of solving problems, whether it be getting back your stolen football or avenging a lost brother. 
    Many falsely criticize that the film still helps to perpetuate violence by citing the violent incidents that were reported at 25 of the 800 theatres where the film opened (‘Boyz’ Film Opens to Violence).  This accusation is ludicrous, seeing as the shootings all occurred prior to or as the film started.  No offensive or violent images appear as the film opens, but rather a harrowing fact hangs lifelessly on the screen: One out of every twenty-one Black American males will be murdered in their lifetime.  By displaying the harsh reality of life as a Black American, an anti-violent tone is set for the film.  To further discourage violence and upheaval, Singleton does not cast any of the characters in specific gangs and sparingly uses gang references at all.  In a press conference in response to the shootings, Singleton said that a segment of the population wants shootings like this to occur and that he will not turn his back on his brothers (‘Boyz’ Film Opens to Violence).  This sage-like advice is very similar to many of the sermons Furious Styles launches into throughout the film.
    Just as the opening sequence clearly sets the tone of an anti-violent message, the character of Furious Styles carries this message through out the movie.  Furious Styles, Tre’s father and model of masculinity, does not immediately stand out from the typical Black American portrayed in film (Massood).  He became a father at a young age, there is no indication he received any higher education and he is unmarried.  Yet it becomes more and more apparent as the film progresses that while Furious was given the same circumstances common to many Black Americans in this setting, he was able to rise above his circumstances and attain a level of enlightenment that gives him a deeper insight into the true problem haunting his people.  Tre and his friends cannot help but respect Furious for this enlightenment.  Furious is continually described as deep and addressed by Ricky as a preacher.  In many ways, that is just what Furious Styles is: a preacher.
    A preacher not only speaks of good news and of salvation, but also of an invisible evil and of temptation.  Furious speaks of many methods of salvation; property ownership, considerate thought and education, just to name a few.  He also speaks of an outside force that is working to tempt his son and neighbors.  This external force drives the land value into the ground by placing liquor stores and gun shops on every corner and supplying crack cocaine to the country.  Ultimately, Furious preaches that this invisible evil wants those in the hood to kill each other, preventing their ability to reproduce themselves.  Of course, a preacher does not call for a direct offense against the devil, but rather that his followers would transform their minds as not be effected by the manipulation techniques the devil employs.  Furious, much in the same manner, calls for Blacks to maintain control of their property and to consider their actions carefully and think about their future rather than naively “smoking” the first brother who makes a threat toward them.  Through these transformations, Furious presents a clear way to weaken the stranglehold on the hood held by this powerful corporate machine, which strives to ensure Blacks continue to murder Blacks.
    Singleton and many of the characters in the film do realize that it is not simply Blacks murdering Blacks, but friends murdering friends.  Doughboy seeks his brother’s killers all night, and finally the crew decides to stop for a meal.  The burger joint they pull into already has a few customers with a similar idea.  Singleton focuses briefly on these customers, Ricky’s killers, and presents them much in the same light as all the other characters are: as likable misfits and consequences of their surroundings.  There is no reason why these characters could not be friends had they met on slightly different circumstances.
    Had other circumstances been slightly different, these characters fates could be drastically different as well.  Had the two sets of hooligans not bumped into each other at Crenshaw, the argument between the groups would not have ensued.  Had Ricky turned the other cheek rather than resulting to foul name calling so quickly, Doughboy would have never had the opportunity to flash his gun, which would’ve never inspired Ricky’s killer from discharging an automatic weapon into the air.  This built up frustration between these two groups of very similar teens eventually ends in the death of almost all present for this encounter.  Of course, it did not have to be this way.  Both sides continued to live by the gun and search for the easiest way to take control in situations of conflict.  At any point in this encounter, if anyone had followed Furious’ advice to think about his future and to avoid the temptation to do what the outside forces want, this whole situation could have been prevented.  
    However, no one followed the advice offered by Furious.  The result is portrayed violently on screen, both as Ricky’s body is impacted in agonizing slow motion and as his killers are gunned down by Doughboy’s drive-by.  As Ricky is shot, an emotional reaction is demanded of the audience.  Ricky is torn from them before their eyes.  The second shooting is not all that different, though.  As Doughboy steps out of the car to fire a few more shells in each body, a very similar emotional reaction is required of the audience again.  As Doughboy demands his brother’s killer turns over the man responds with a strange plea.  He insists that he did not pull the trigger.  Doughboy knows this is a lie, yet a strange look comes across his face.  From this look the audience realizes that Doughboy was just ripped from them just as Ricky was, and not simply because Doughboy is now ill fated.  Ricky’s killer and his killer have suddenly become enlightened and realized what Furious has been preaching all along:  They are simply playing their roles as puppets to a society that wants them dead.  Doughboy’s face does not express satisfaction, achievement or glory, but rather emptiness and guilt.  He suddenly realizes why Tre asked him to pull the car over, and he wishes he had gotten out too.
    Many of the solutions Furious preached are as simple as pulling the car over and walking home, the path Tre finally decided upon.  His decision legitimizes himself as a man and as a model.  It is for that reason that Tre has no words for his father upon returning home, still covered in his friend’s blood.  He has faced one of the most troubling of events and been able to rise above his emotions and think, just as Furious always stressed.  On top of that he has proven that he made the decision for himself, not for his father.  He is an adult, he knows what he did and he does not need to explain his guiltless actions to anyone.  The call of the movie is to challenge each and every viewer to do the same: To take the message preached by Furious and make it your own.  Singleton starts the movie with a harrowing fact about the realities of Black American’s and ends the film with a final plea to his audience in the same fashion: Increase the Peace.  This message of anti-violence through any means necessary is strongly demonstrated throughout every facet of the film, be it the respect Furious demands and the message he preaches or the portrayal of the antagonists as congruent with the protagonists.  For every violent image displayed on the screen, the filmgoer is bombarded with messages from various angles of the cost of such violence.  This barrage is so strong it would be improbably that any patron who could legally screen the film could leave with a sense that the violence was a desirable escape or solution to any of the numerous conflicts shown throughout the film.  This film undoubtedly has and will continue to ‘Increase the Peace.’

Works Cited.
Massood, Paula J.  “From Homeboy to Baby Boy: Masculinity and Violence in the Films of John
Singleton.
Harris, Scott, and Jim Herron Zamora. "'Boyz' Film Opens to Violence." Los Angeles Times 
14 July 1991: 3.
