Assignment 5
City of Angels and Devils
    No single event has watermarked the image of Los Angeles in the American consciousness quite like the Los Angeles Riots of 1992.  Like the faded face of Jefferson on the twenty dollar bill, one will not merely notice the way the riots transformed the City of Angels by happenstance.  Yet, if the city is examined with deliberate intent it is difficult to miss:  gated communities around every corner, fortress-like structures housing the middle class and the relentless flight to distance oneself from the city one’s life revolves around.  The riots are not the sole catalyst of this heightened security, but more precisely, the causes of the riots were the catalysts.  The riots are, however, the best defined face of the alienation that has created in the citizens of Los Angeles an “us or them” mentality.  This separatist mentality not only shapes Los Angeles, but it actually defines it through race relations on a socio-geographical level.
    Were the riots simply a natural disaster, the reaction of a society would not be a proper gauge of the mentality of its citizens.  A natural disaster gives a window of the mentality a city has in a state of emergency, but a self-inflicted disaster is able to more holistically define the mentality that both caused and reacted to the disaster.  In this environmentalist era, natural disasters are precisely defined as having causes that are in no way dependant upon human-environment interaction.  The riots are often described as inevitable, but there is almost as frequently an unspoken clause tagged to such a description: given the way races were alienated.  The riots came about as a result of straws of injustice, such as the beating of motorist Rodney King, burdening the black community. The April 29th acquittal, not simply the prodigal back-breaking straw, sparked an inferno of burning straw that was long overdue for a wildfire.  Since the riots are clearly the result of citizens’ mentalities, the reactionary thoughts and dialogues can accurately define the characteristics of a city as a whole.  The most central of these characteristics is the feeling of alienation experienced.
    One of the most comprehensive collections of dialogue from the aftermath of the riots came about in the form of “documentary theatre” researched and assembled by actress Anna Deavere Smith.  She is improperly given credit for writing Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992, although she did not write a single line of dialogue.  Every word is taken from interviews she conducted with persons of interest or disinterest in the wake of the 1992 riots.  Those interviewed range from people directly involved within the riots, including a police officer indicted for the beating, to those involved only by proximity, such as an anonymous USC student relatively safe in her sorority house.  While documentary is always subject to the documenter’s notions and message, it is relatively safe to assume Smith tried to stay as true to the voices she heard as possible.  Her message, as stated in the introduction of the play, is a call to the community to resolve the problems that created the tensions that allowed the riots to come to fruition (Smith XXIV).  Those closest to the riot, the community she is speaking of, would surely see through an overtly dramatized sampling of hatred still harbored between races, and that community would not be drawn to motion if Smith had censored the work to tame the topics presented.  While this logic cannot fully rule out subconscious or deliberate sampling of phrases vital to an agenda, it does show that Smith would have no clear motive for such an action.  Therefore, the voices presented within the dialogue of Twilight are as good as any to represent the mentality that led up and made possible the Rodney King Riots.
    Although the scenes are broken down into lengthy monologues, they are better understood when considered as dialogue between Smith and the interviewee.  One way to think about this is to consider all the epiphanies experienced by Smith while conducting such interviews.  Smith cannot simply explain these epiphanies to us due to the constraints of the play.  Therefore she makes every attempt to best recreate this dialogue casting each audience member as the role of Anna Deavere Smith, showcasing the interviews that would be best suited for bringing about these epiphanies.  Of course, the constraints of the play were assigned by Smith herself, so she must have felt that it would be most effective way of encouraging the audience member to make his or her own decisions about the dialogue spoken.  Since the audience members are actively spoken to and actively coerced into make tough decisions, it is more appropriate to call the long blocks of one person’s story dialogue.  When thought of in this way, one can see that the mentalities exuberated by the interviewees are not far from those of audience members either.
    The mentalities represented in Smith’s play range from hatred to forgiveness.  Yet one mentality stands out strongly throughout all the dialogues: the sense of alienation.  This alienation creates a feeling that there are devils and angels at work in Los Angeles.  Rudy Salas, Sr., at a very young age, “realized [he] had an enemy and that enemy was those nice white teachers” (Smith 2).  He says he does not know why he understood about the white teachers, but that he knew they were his enemy regardless.  It was ingrained in him.  He was Mexican and thus could only truly depend on Mexicans.  He could not trust the police force to protect him in a time of need as he had been too badly mistreated by them in the past.  When a man cannot trust the police, he needs to make efforts to find his own form of security.  Salas reinforces this claim by explaining that he educated his sons to “cooperate… let [the police] call you what they want,” but goes on to say “tell me who they are” (Smith 6).  Salas understood that he would have to protect his sons and his race himself, even if it meant physically fighting his enemy.
    Most astonishing is that Salas or Mexican Americans in general are not alone in feeling alienated by other races.  June Park, whose husband Walter Park was shot by a black man while driving, expresses her doubts about the fairness of her husband’s resulting lobotomy.  She explains that her Korean husband was not only a good man, but specifically donated “a lot of money” to Compton, a predominantly black neighborhood (Smith 147).  Her husband, who was innocent of even crimes of ignorance against blacks, was shot in a traffic dispute presumably based entirely on his race.  Her son explains that the driver actually broke the driver’s side window and shot him “almost execution style” (Smith 149).  Walter Park, despite his lobotomized state, is able to articulate his desire to return to Korea (Smith 143).  He pieces together in broken English an idea that he could change the situation if he were there (Smith 143).  While it is difficult to speculate precisely what situation he means, it would have to be one that could be changed from Korea, so it presumably has nothing to do with race relations in Los Angeles but more likely his loneliness or his wife’s sadness.  Although he has fought the idea of racial separatism, with his frontal lobe (where his “higher learning skills are” according to his stepson, a medical student) removed, he cannot suppress the idea ingrained in him that life might be better if he were surrounded by more Koreans (Smith 146).  While Walter Park does not use language as strong as Salas’, his message is the same: he and his people are what will make him and his family happy and keep them safe.
    Black leaders expressed a similar sense. If things were going to change it was not the government that was going to do it, but the blacks alone.  Former head of the Black Panther Party, Elaine Brown, exposes the foolishness of blacks declaring to war on the United States government (Smith 230).  She does not expose the naivety by explaining that blacks are a part of this government, but solely on the basis that they will lose to the United States Army (Smith 230).  The very idea of blacks declaring a war on the government implies that they do not consider themselves a part of it and that they do not see the US Army as an army that protects them.  They can only rely on each other, their own kind, for safety and justice.  Black Congresswoman Maxine Waters agrees during her speech at the First African Methodist Episcopal Church.  She indicates that journalists and politicians pressured her to tell rioters to “cool it” and then deliberately refuses to make such a statement, instead rationalizing riots as “the voice of the unheard” (Smith 161-62).  She has the same feeling that her race must stick together and claim justice themselves, even if it means literally taking Los Angeles hostage.  The system cannot help them so they must help each other.
    However it is not only the minorities that felt the need to stick together and watch out for their race.  A startling, yet unanimous ruling from the California Court of Appeals allowed the case to be tried in the predominantly white and conservative Semi Valley (Linder).  Furthermore a jury composed of 10 whites and no blacks failed to acquit three of the officers and were unable to reach a verdict on the fourth, despite the prosecution having arguable the best evidence in any civil rights violation case to date, video footage of the brutal beating (Linder).  The jurors and their families were harassed ceaselessly by black rioters after the verdict was announced.  Jurors were alienated by the non-white community.  While these individual cases certainly cannot prove the existence of a separatist mentality in whites, they are useful in reinforcing such a claim.  Even more reinforcing is the general fear of black neighborhoods among whites while the blacks are equally fearful of white cops.  Nonetheless, it seems everyone is afraid of everyone else.
    Los Angeles’ most defining characteristic is clearly the separatist attitude expressed by each racial classification.  It is not only ingrained through past generations and current events but even in the way the city blocks are arranged by ethnic groups.  Everyone involved in the riots directly or indirectly all had one thing in common: They all felt alienated.  Although everyone thought they were alienated, this common ground played no part in bringing these diverse groups of people together.  So it should come as no surprise that this is a city of Angels and Devils, each defined differently by each race.  It should also come as no surprise that its citizens live in fortresses with private security forces and that every attempt is made to live as close to Los Angeles as possible without having to associate oneself as being a citizen of Los Angeles.  Rodney King’s famous words “Can we all just get along?” was not to encourage rioters to get along with rioters, but rather at each race involved.  The answer, as far as L. A. is concerned is yes, but in an unsteady peace with little harmony as long as everyone continues to alienate one another.








Works Cited 
