Smith, Anna D. Twilight Los Angeles, 1992. New York: Anchor, 1994.  
David Luke Richardson
Writing 140
JJ Strong
April 2, 2006
Extra Credit

On Sunday at 8pm, I attended USC’s performance of Twilight.  All of the monologues were emotionally riveting, but probably the most for me was Bill Bradbury’s story about his black friend being pulled from a car on his way to an internship and his female companion in the car being asked if she was being taken against her will.
I found myself struggling to determine whether I had really enjoyed the director’s choice to associate each actor with characters of different races.  I understand her intent, to show that these problems are universal of all classes and races, but I am just not sure if a white male can ever play a Korean female, just to name an example, without simply portraying a stereotype.  I think it would have been more effective if no attempt at emulating accents or mannerisms had been implemented.  I think it would be a more powerful statement since one could sit and listen to any of the monologues for a few minutes before glancing up at the projector that always displayed the current person’s name and ethnicity and be stunned to find out that these are the words of someone from a different race than you would’ve originally guessed.  
I respect the other choices the director made, though.  I think the jury box set was very clever and the tables and chairs being crafted to look like the LA Skyline while tilted on their sides was a nice touch.  Overall, it was a great experience and it was very informative.  I think it will be a great help in interpreting the text for my final paper.
